<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1888-11-24T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1888-11-24T00:00:00-05:00" n="172" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d172">
                        <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Herbert</persName> to Mr.
                                    <persName type="to">Bayard</persName>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1888-11-24"><hi rend="italic">November</hi> 24,
                                    1888</date>. (Received November 26.)</dateline></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: With reference to your note of yesterday’s
                            date, asking for an early settlement of the <hi rend="italic">Bridgewater</hi> case, I have the honor to inform you that I
                            telegraphed to Her Majesty’s principal secretary of state <pb facs="0590" n="468" xml:id="pg_468"/> for foreign affairs, in the
                            sense of your above-mentioned note, and have received a reply stating
                            that the owner of the <hi rend="italic">Bridgewater</hi>, before
                            presenting the claim, commenced an action at law which is still pending,
                            and that the Canadian Government is unable to express an opinion on the
                            claim until the settlement of the case in the law courts.</p>
                        <p>I have, etc.,</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Arthur Herbert.</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>